 @LethalWalou  I did feel he reacted slowly, but when I saw the full slomo replay, you do have a point. This is a well known effect in road safety. It's the accordion effect. When an incident happens, the cars behind are likely to rear end each other as there is unexpected braking. However, it's not the immediate cars behind. Usually the closest cars can see the original incident and prepare to slow. The car that usually rear ends first, is the first car that is unable to see the original incident. In this case, the car is reacting to the braking of the car in front alone and not the incident which is a much shorter window. You can see on Stroll's onboard he can't see Alonso at all.

You see this happen in a lot of turn 1 lap 1 incidents. Where a car just seems to not brake a few cars behind but not immediately behind the original incident.
 And people go, he didn't even try to brake! not realizing the reasons why that type of accident happens.

